If the obstruction takes place in the former, the mass of the blood will lack its due ferment, the influx of fermentative spirits being shut off from the spleen3 but if the latter are ob- structed, the saline-sulphureous particles of the blood detained too long in the parenchyma of the spleen and too much fermented, will acquire an acid and dried up, or what is the same thing, an atrabilous character.

2. lf the substance of the spleen is corroded by an ulcer, or in any other way broken, the nitro-a'e‘rial particles will not now as at other times be mixed in its parenchyma intimately and uniformly with the mass of the blood, but in a too crowded and confused way, whence a too intense effervescence is set up, on account of which the saline-sulphureous particles of the blood become much dried up and sooty.

Fronr what has been said, it is not difficult to understand how it is that an animal can live when deprived of so notable an organ as the spleen; for although the offices here assigned to the spleen conduce in no small degree to the correct carrying on of the animal economy and to perfect health, still they are not so necessary but that life can be kept up in a so-so way without them.
